<whois_lookup_guide>
<title>WHOIS AND DOMAIN OSINT ANALYSIS</title>

<critical>WHOIS data reveals domain ownership, registration history, and organizational relationships. Even with privacy protection, patterns in registrar, nameservers, creation dates, and historical records expose infrastructure connections, enable related domain discovery, and provide social engineering vectors. WHOIS is the starting point for mapping an organization's digital footprint.</critical>

<scope>
- Domain registration data extraction
- Registrant, admin, and tech contact analysis
- Privacy protection bypass techniques
- Historical WHOIS data mining
- Related domain discovery
- Registrar and reseller identification
- Expiration and renewal tracking
- Nameserver relationship mapping
- Organization and infrastructure correlation
- Reverse WHOIS lookups
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Query current WHOIS data for target domains.
2. Identify registrant organization and contact details.
3. Analyze nameserver patterns and hosting providers.
4. Query historical WHOIS for ownership changes.
5. Perform reverse WHOIS on discovered identifiers.
6. Map related domains through shared attributes.
7. Identify registration patterns and naming conventions.
8. Check domain expiration for potential hijacking.
9. Correlate findings with other OSINT sources.
10. Document organizational structure and relationships.
</methodology>

<testing_techniques>
<basic_whois>
{% raw %}
# Basic WHOIS Queries

# Command-line WHOIS
whois example.com

# Specify WHOIS server
whois -h whois.verisign-grs.com example.com

# Query specific TLD servers
# .com/.net: whois.verisign-grs.com
# .org:      whois.pir.org
# .io:       whois.nic.io
# .co:       whois.nic.co
# .info:     whois.afilias.net

# Key fields to extract:
# Domain Name: example.com
# Registry Domain ID: unique identifier
# Registrar WHOIS Server: registrar's WHOIS
# Registrar URL: registrar website
# Updated Date: last modification
# Creation Date: domain age
# Registry Expiry Date: renewal deadline
# Registrar: company name
# Registrar IANA ID: unique registrar ID
# Registrar Abuse Contact Email/Phone
# Domain Status: clientTransferProhibited, etc.
# Name Server: ns1.example.com, ns2.example.com
# DNSSEC: signed/unsigned

# Registrant/Admin/Tech Contact:
# Name, Organization, Street, City, State, Postal, Country
# Phone, Email
{% endraw %}
</basic_whois>

<domain_status_codes>
{% raw %}
# WHOIS Status Codes (EPP Status)

# Client-side locks (registrant/registrar controlled)
clientDeleteProhibited     # Cannot be deleted
clientTransferProhibited   # Cannot be transferred
clientUpdateProhibited     # Cannot be modified
clientHold                 # Not resolving (suspended by registrar)

# Server-side locks (registry controlled)
serverDeleteProhibited     # Registry lock
serverTransferProhibited   # Registry lock
serverUpdateProhibited     # Registry lock
serverHold                 # Registry suspended

# Lifecycle statuses
addPeriod                  # Recently registered (5 day grace)
autoRenewPeriod           # Auto-renewed, can be deleted
redemptionPeriod          # Deleted, can be restored (30 days)
pendingRestore            # Restoration requested
pendingDelete             # Will be deleted soon
pendingTransfer           # Transfer in progress
pendingCreate             # Registration in progress

# Security-relevant
clientTransferProhibited  # Good: prevents unauthorized transfer
serverTransferProhibited  # Registry-level protection
clientDeleteProhibited    # Prevents accidental deletion

# Warning signs
clientHold / serverHold   # Domain suspended
pendingDelete             # About to be available
redemptionPeriod          # Owner may have lost control
{% endraw %}
</domain_status_codes>

